It's Nanomichi.

05:00.533 --> 05:02.626
You know, the god
of storm and thunder.

05:02.669 --> 05:04.603
- Cool, huh?
- Okay, come on, hurry up

05:04.637 --> 05:05.604
before it dries.

05:05.638 --> 05:06.605
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

05:06.639 --> 05:08.129
Okay, ready?

05:08.174 --> 05:09.436
Here, give me
your foot.

05:09.475 --> 05:10.942
The secret tattoo.

05:11.010 --> 05:13.877
My best friends Sport,
Janie and I thought

05:13.913 --> 05:15.778
we should be blood buddies.

05:15.815 --> 05:18.181
But this was so much
less painful.

05:20.853 --> 05:22.684
Just remember the rule.

05:22.722 --> 05:25.714
If anyone sees
the secret tattoo...

05:25.758 --> 05:28.192
...swift and painful death.

05:37.804 --> 05:41.035
It's... starting.

05:42.675 --> 05:45.576
Here comes...

05:45.611 --> 05:49.980
nice Marion Hawthorne.

05:50.049 --> 05:51.311
It's happening.

05:51.351 --> 05:53.444
I can feel it happening.

05:53.486 --> 05:54.885
Good Lord.

05:54.921 --> 05:56.946
It's the dreaded
Hawthorne effect.

05:59.058 --> 06:00.389
Oh.

06:05.431 --> 06:07.922
Good morning, Janie, Simon...

06:08.000 --> 06:09.900
and Harriet.

06:11.270 --> 06:13.329
Harri... et!

06:13.373 --> 06:16.240
I got to get to class.

06:16.275 --> 06:18.072
See ya.

06:18.111 --> 06:20.170
See you guys in a few.

06:23.282 --> 06:24.977
Sixth grade.

06:26.486 --> 06:31.924
All the usual suspects
are back in action.

06:31.958 --> 06:35.758
First of all there's
Rachel Hennessy,

06:35.795 --> 06:37.956
Marion's second in command.

06:38.064 --> 06:41.431
The only thing more pathetic
than being Marion Hawthorne

06:41.467 --> 06:44.959
is wanting to be
Marion Hawthorne.

06:47.340 --> 06:49.069
Pinky Whitehead,

06:49.108 --> 06:51.099
the human fish belly.

06:51.144 --> 06:53.510
If Janie's theory is right,
then Pinky's DNA

06:53.546 --> 06:56.379
was combined with a pint
of vanilla yogurt at birth.

06:56.416 --> 06:59.010
Carrie Andrews thinks
she's cool...

07:00.653 --> 07:03.087
'cause she spent her summer
vacation growing boobs.

07:05.758 --> 07:08.784
Laura Peters looks like
someone pinched her face

07:08.828 --> 07:11.160
and it stuck that way.

07:11.197 --> 07:13.631
The boy with purple socks.

07:13.666 --> 07:15.759
A man of mystery.

07:15.802 --> 07:17.736
He never talks.

07:17.770 --> 07:20.933
If I were known
only by my footwear,

07:20.973 --> 07:22.907
I'd hang myself.

07:22.942 --> 07:26.673
Beth Ellen Hansen always looks
like she's about to cry.

07:26.712 --> 07:29.078
I wish someone
would just kick her

07:29.115 --> 07:30.605
and get it over with.

07:32.285 --> 07:35.083
And then of course,
there's our teacher...

07:35.121 --> 07:36.554
Miss Elson.

07:36.589 --> 07:38.853
She's nice, and polite.

07:38.891 --> 07:41.587
I bet one day she goes
on a psycho killing spree,

07:41.627 --> 07:43.390
and all her neighbors
will say...

07:43.429 --> 07:45.420
"She was nice and polite."

07:45.465 --> 07:49.299
Well, from what your last
two teachers tell me,

07:49.335 --> 07:52.202
it looks like
dÃ©ja vu all over again.

07:57.043 --> 08:01.377
It's time to vote for
a sixth grade class president.

08:01.414 --> 08:05.316
And for the third year
in a row...

08:05.351 --> 08:08.445
we're down to our final
two nominees,

08:08.488 --> 08:12.185
and they are Harriet Welsch

08:12.225 --> 08:15.285
and Marion Hawthorne.

08:15.328 --> 08:19.059
And so, as you may know,

08:19.098 --> 08:22.033
the duties of the class
president include

08:22.068 --> 08:26.402
taking attendance,
reporting bad behavior

08:26.439 --> 08:32.707
and best of all, editing
the sixth grade newspaper.

08:34.981 --> 08:37.245
And now we vote.

08:38.650 --> 08:42.178
Marion Hawthorne... again.

08:42.221 --> 08:45.054
Three years in a row.

08:45.091 --> 08:48.458
You know what?
I think I'll invent a poison.

08:48.494 --> 08:49.483
A really good,

08:49.529 --> 08:51.656
clean, untraceable poison.

08:51.697 --> 08:53.164
One that fries your brains

08:53.199 --> 08:55.667
and makes all your bodily
fluids boil at once.

08:55.701 --> 08:56.963
- Could you?
- Check it out.

08:57.069 --> 08:59.401
One day I'd be like,
"Oh, hi, Marion.

08:59.438 --> 09:01.429
"Oh, no, I'm not
finishing this soda."

09:01.474 --> 09:02.634
And she'd be like...

09:09.181 --> 09:11.115
I'm serious.

09:11.150 --> 09:12.777
Any of you guys
want to come over?

09:12.818 --> 09:13.876
I got to get home.

09:13.920 --> 09:15.751
If my amoebas start
incubating,

09:15.788 --> 09:17.619
they really stink up the house.

09:17.657 --> 09:18.783
Harriet?

09:18.824 --> 09:20.792
Sorry. Spy time.

09:53.058 --> 09:55.322
Spy route.

09:55.360 --> 09:57.191
Harrison Withers' place.

09:57.228 --> 09:59.389
Higher altitude, lower risk.

09:59.431 --> 10:00.830
But always a show.

10:05.170 --> 10:09.163
Yeah, everybody's gonna have
some grease today...

10:09.207 --> 10:14.509
All right, now, Jelly Roll.
Yeah.

10:14.546 --> 10:17.071
Lady Day

10:17.115 --> 10:20.573
Come what may,
whatever you say

10:20.618 --> 10:22.483
We all gonna have
a good time

10:22.520 --> 10:24.681
A little bit
for you, Satchmo

10:24.723 --> 10:26.213
You, Bessie

10:26.257 --> 10:28.657
And how 'bout you,
Jelly Roll?

10:28.693 --> 10:31.924
Golly says, people
who love work love life.

10:31.963 --> 10:33.123
Dizzy, Dizzy

10:33.164 --> 10:34.995
I like Harrison Withers,

10:35.066 --> 10:37.728
'cause he's a guy
that loves both.

10:37.769 --> 10:39.828
Scooby dah...

10:39.871 --> 10:41.702
Scooby-dooby, du-day

10:41.740 --> 10:43.970
Okay, that's it.

10:48.113 --> 10:50.013
Curiously, Harrison lives

10:50.048 --> 10:51.640
for his cats.

10:51.683 --> 10:53.913
Wow! Birdland.

10:56.388 --> 10:58.879
But his work is for the birds.

11:01.993 --> 11:04.154
Charlie Parker.

11:04.195 --> 11:06.755
Yardbird.

11:06.798 --> 11:10.700
In any case, his cages
are the most beautiful

11:10.735 --> 11:12.066
I've ever seen.

11:43.234 --> 11:44.496
It's him.

11:44.536 --> 11:47.004
The Health Department
has it in for Harrison,

11:47.105 --> 11:49.266
'cause they say he's got
too many cats.

11:50.341 --> 11:52.002
I know, I know.

11:52.077 --> 11:56.138
Too bad for them,
Harrison has a system.

11:56.181 --> 11:58.775
See a hat, don't be home.

11:58.817 --> 12:02.048
No hat, no problem.

12:04.656 --> 12:08.114
Another score for the cat fan.

12:19.504 --> 12:20.869
Hey.

12:20.905 --> 12:22.964
Hey.

12:23.007 --> 12:24.372
Want some necklace?

12:24.409 --> 12:26.639
How about you, man?

12:26.678 --> 12:28.908
Ew. You got it all spitty.

12:28.947 --> 12:30.778
Tastes better that way.

12:30.815 --> 12:31.975
Good.

12:32.016 --> 12:33.984
Hey, Harriet,
what are you writing?

12:34.018 --> 12:35.144
Notes.

12:35.186 --> 12:36.483
Can we read them?

12:36.521 --> 12:38.648
Can you read this?

12:38.690 --> 12:39.657
Okay, okay.

12:39.691 --> 12:40.680
I just wanted to know

12:40.725 --> 12:42.625
why you're always
writing like a maniac.

12:42.660 --> 12:44.651
I want to remember everything.

12:44.696 --> 12:46.425
I want to know everything.

12:46.464 --> 12:47.863
Well, you must realize, Harriet,

12:47.899 --> 12:49.890
knowing everything
won't do you a bit of good

12:49.934 --> 12:51.993
unless you use it to put
beauty in this world.

12:52.070 --> 12:53.264
True or false?

12:53.304 --> 12:53.998
True.

12:54.038 --> 12:55.005
Of course it is.

12:55.039 --> 12:56.438
Harriet, your mother called.

12:56.474 --> 12:57.634
She's going to be late.

12:57.675 --> 12:58.801
Come on, Sport, Janie.

12:58.843 --> 13:00.470
I'll have you home
before dinner.

13:00.512 --> 13:02.377
Golly always takes us places.

13:02.413 --> 13:05.382
She sees things
other people barely notice.

13:05.416 --> 13:09.853
She's my nanny and...
well, she's Golly.

13:09.888 --> 13:11.446
Okay, survey of the day.

13:11.489 --> 13:12.888
Today's question is:

13:12.924 --> 13:14.824
What wouldn't you eat
for a million dollars?

13:14.859 --> 13:16.759
Bratwurst.

13:16.794 --> 13:17.761
Sport?

13:17.795 --> 13:21.128
Um... camel boogers,
dried roadkill,

13:21.166 --> 13:22.929
and my dad's meatloaf.

13:22.967 --> 13:24.127
Janie?

13:27.238 --> 13:30.833
It's the last day of summer.

13:30.875 --> 13:32.900
Sad but true.

13:32.944 --> 13:35.310
Au revoir, monsieur soleil.

13:35.346 --> 13:36.973
Farewell!

13:37.048 --> 13:37.980
So long, bye-bye.

13:38.049 --> 13:38.981
Sayonara!

13:39.050 --> 13:41.314
- Good-bye...
- We're here.

13:46.658 --> 13:47.989
Is this a garden?

13:48.059 --> 13:48.991
What a place!

13:49.060 --> 13:49.992
What is this?

13:50.061 --> 13:51.221
Golly, what's that?

13:51.262 --> 13:54.254
That's Mrs. W.,
a very good friend of mine.

13:54.299 --> 13:55.561
Kind of unusual.

13:55.600 --> 13:57.568
You know, there are as many ways
to live

13:57.602 --> 13:59.001
as there are people
in this world.

13:59.070 --> 14:01.470
And each one
deserves a closer look.

14:01.506 --> 14:03.337
Welcome!

14:03.374 --> 14:04.568
Come on in.

14:04.609 --> 14:05.576
Hi.

14:05.610 --> 14:06.577
- Hi.
- Hi.

14:06.611 --> 14:07.839
Hi.

14:07.879 --> 14:09.938
Look around.

14:10.014 --> 14:11.709
Have fun.

14:13.451 --> 14:15.419
Whoa! Awesome!

14:23.261 --> 14:24.319
Bop, bop, bop, bop!

14:32.837 --> 14:34.634
Do-wat, do-wat, do-wat

14:34.672 --> 14:36.037
I'm goin'!

14:41.779 --> 14:44.179
Ooh.

14:57.695 --> 14:58.627
I'm goin'!

15:05.503 --> 15:06.595
Hey, you guys...

15:06.638 --> 15:09.129
what do you say
I propose a toast?

15:09.173 --> 15:11.607
Come on.

15:14.946 --> 15:16.709
Oh... go away.

15:16.748 --> 15:18.716
Say it quick, before
it stops fizzing.

15:18.750 --> 15:21.241
Shake it up, take a sip,
and wish for what you want

15:21.286 --> 15:22.253
most in the world.

15:22.287 --> 15:23.754
Okay.

15:23.788 --> 15:26.154
I want to replicate
my own DNA

15:26.190 --> 15:27.919
and win
the Nobel Peace Prize. Yeah.

15:29.661 --> 15:30.628
Oh!

15:30.662 --> 15:31.788
Very good, Janie.

15:31.829 --> 15:32.853
Okay, shake it up, Sport.

15:32.897 --> 15:33.886
Shake it up.

15:33.931 --> 15:35.523
I want to play
more baseball games

15:35.566 --> 15:36.658
than Cal Ripkin, Jr.

15:36.701 --> 15:37.998
Oh, yeah!

15:38.936 --> 15:41.097
And get filthy rich doing it.

15:41.139 --> 15:42.128
Oh, yeah!

15:42.173 --> 15:44.971
Shake it, Harriet.

15:45.076 --> 15:46.634
I want to see the whole world

15:46.678 --> 15:48.669
and I want to write down
everything.

15:57.455 --> 15:58.717
Harriet, slow down.

15:58.756 --> 16:01.316
That's very impressive.

16:01.359 --> 16:02.553
Harriet?

16:03.628 --> 16:04.595
I'm goin'!

16:04.629 --> 16:05.721
That's good, Harriet.

16:05.763 --> 16:07.128
That's very pretty,
isn't it, Janie?

16:07.165 --> 16:08.154
Yes, I like it.

16:10.401 --> 16:11.663
Got you!

16:31.356 --> 16:33.119
Hey, wait up.

16:36.095 --> 16:38.757
Everybody, hello!
It sucks, sixth grade!

16:38.797 --> 16:40.162
Feet off the bed, please.

16:40.199 --> 16:41.894
Okay.

16:44.270 --> 16:45.294
Feet off.

16:45.337 --> 16:46.736
Oh, the heinie bounce.

16:46.772 --> 16:47.739
Good choice.

16:47.773 --> 16:49.240
Very cute, Harriet,
very cute.

16:49.275 --> 16:50.572
The neighbors
will ask me,

16:50.609 --> 16:52.304
"What happened
to Harriet Welsch?"

16:52.344 --> 16:53.311
"I don't know,"
I'll answer.

16:53.345 --> 16:54.312
"Such a shame.

16:54.346 --> 16:56.541
"She disappeared
without a trace.

16:56.582 --> 16:58.709
And she was
so adorable."

16:58.751 --> 17:00.776
How long have you been
with me, Golly?

17:00.819 --> 17:02.343
Since you were born.

17:02.388 --> 17:05.289
11 years and
12,000 tomato sandwiches ago.

17:05.324 --> 17:07.258
And you'll never leave me,
right?

17:07.292 --> 17:09.157
Well, I won't leave you
"leave you," Harriet,

17:09.194 --> 17:11.425
but, you know, one day
you're going to be big enough.

17:11.463 --> 17:14.626
And well... well, big enough
to take care of yourself.

17:14.666 --> 17:15.759
And when that day comes

17:15.800 --> 17:17.530
you won't need me
and I'll be gone.

17:17.569 --> 17:19.127
But you know what?

17:19.171 --> 17:21.138
That day is not today.

17:21.173 --> 17:22.935
And now, it's time for bed.

17:22.974 --> 17:24.738
Are Mom and Dad
tucking me in?

17:24.777 --> 17:25.743
No.

17:25.778 --> 17:27.769
They're at a very fancy party

17:27.813 --> 17:30.873
and I bet they're thinking
about you right now. Really.

17:30.916 --> 17:33.407
Listen, I think I can hear 'em.

17:33.452 --> 17:35.352
Harriet...

17:35.387 --> 17:38.356
listen to everything
Golly says to you.

17:38.390 --> 17:42.383
We're drinking champagne
and eating caviar, Harriet.

17:42.428 --> 17:43.759
Come on.

17:43.796 --> 17:46.094
Let's go to bed.

17:46.131 --> 17:47.598
Who's going to bed?

17:47.633 --> 17:49.191
Uh, you are, tough guy.

17:49.235 --> 17:50.702
- Come on.
- Ow! Ow!

17:50.736 --> 17:51.725
Child abuse! Child abuse!

17:51.770 --> 17:53.135
Oh, you think
that's child abuse?

17:53.172 --> 17:54.639
You haven't even...
How about that?

17:54.673 --> 17:56.402
What about that?
What about one of these?

17:58.844 --> 18:01.438
Stand still,
you little booger.

18:01.480 --> 18:03.107
Ugh!

18:05.484 --> 18:07.645
I'm telling you,
just give me the big knife

18:07.686 --> 18:09.051
and this will all be over.

18:09.088 --> 18:10.749
Harriet, dear,
you have taken

18:10.789 --> 18:12.916
a tomato sandwich
to school with you...

18:12.958 --> 18:13.925
With mayonnaise.

18:13.959 --> 18:15.256
...with mayonnaise
every day

18:15.294 --> 18:16.522
for that past five years.

18:16.562 --> 18:17.586
Don't you want
a little variety?

18:17.630 --> 18:18.597
Nope.

18:18.631 --> 18:21.395
Not even cream cheese
with olive?

18:21.433 --> 18:22.491
Yum-yum-yum!

18:22.534 --> 18:25.162
Or how about pastrami?
Roast beef?

18:25.204 --> 18:27.764
How about the fancy
cucumber kind,

18:27.806 --> 18:29.671
with the crust cut off?

18:29.708 --> 18:33.644
Mom, I can't help it
if I know what I like.

18:33.679 --> 18:36.546
And I know that I like tomato.

18:47.526 --> 18:50.051
After school spy route...

18:50.095 --> 18:52.689
Hong Fat's Food Emporium

19:41.747 --> 19:44.477
Holy cats, a veggie thief.

19:44.516 --> 19:46.746
This must be investigated
thoroughly.

19:58.063 --> 20:00.759
Frankie, you took the truck
last week.

20:00.799 --> 20:02.664
Wasn't that enough?

20:02.701 --> 20:03.793
Stop walking around.

20:03.836 --> 20:06.168
Frankie, go do some homework.

20:06.205 --> 20:07.331
I've done my homework.

20:07.373 --> 20:08.340
Do some reading.

20:08.374 --> 20:09.602
Watch TV.
Do something.

20:09.641 --> 20:11.108
Grandpa, all I need
is the truck.

20:11.143 --> 20:12.371
I know you know
that I mean.

20:16.582 --> 20:18.379
Come on, Ma,
let me have the truck.

20:20.586 --> 20:21.553
I got a date!

20:21.587 --> 20:23.145
What do you take me for?

20:23.188 --> 20:26.316
The Hong Fats have a son...
Frankie.

20:26.358 --> 20:28.656
He's cool; American style.

20:28.694 --> 20:30.992
His parents are
Chinese-style cool.

20:31.029 --> 20:32.656
Frankie likes going out,

20:32.698 --> 20:34.996
but they'd rather
he work in the store,

20:35.033 --> 20:38.298
selling milk and bread
and lizards.

20:39.571 --> 20:41.539
Ugh!

20:52.317 --> 20:55.753
I mean, do I try to interfere
with your bookkeeping?!

20:55.788 --> 20:57.016
My business is comedy!

20:57.055 --> 20:58.249
That's what I do!

20:58.290 --> 20:59.848
I'm funny!
I'm the funny guy!

20:59.892 --> 21:00.859
Yes, you are.

21:00.893 --> 21:02.554
They're the money guys.

21:02.594 --> 21:03.561
Okay, slippery,

21:03.595 --> 21:04.562
bath time's over.

21:04.596 --> 21:05.824
Come out with your hands up.

21:05.864 --> 21:06.831
But I just got in.

21:06.865 --> 21:08.457
Oh, sure.
I believe that one.

21:08.500 --> 21:10.468
Let's see your fingers,
prune girl.

21:10.502 --> 21:12.299
Talk to the hand,
'cause the face

21:12.337 --> 21:13.429
ain't gonna listen.

21:13.472 --> 21:15.099
He asked me to come up

21:15.140 --> 21:16.903
with something new,
something fresh.

21:16.942 --> 21:18.170
You read it.
It was good.

21:18.210 --> 21:19.734
- Yes.
- It was the funniest script

21:19.778 --> 21:20.767
we've had all year!

21:20.813 --> 21:22.542
Yes, it was. So what
was their problem?

21:22.581 --> 21:24.071
Hey, I want to hear.

21:24.116 --> 21:26.380
Oh, yeah?
I want to sing opera,

21:26.418 --> 21:28.249
but I can't, so I don't.

21:28.287 --> 21:29.447
That downstairs is...

21:29.488 --> 21:34.323
Well, your dad
has a high-pressure job.

21:34.359 --> 21:35.656
What's a high-pressure job?

21:35.694 --> 21:37.628
It's when you don't
get to do what you want

21:37.663 --> 21:38.687
and when you do,

21:38.730 --> 21:39.992
you don't have time to do it.

21:40.032 --> 21:42.865
Do spies have
high-pressure jobs?

21:42.901 --> 21:44.664
Only when
they're caught.

21:44.703 --> 21:46.000
I'm never caught.

21:46.038 --> 21:47.198
You're right.

21:47.239 --> 21:48.399
You never are.

21:48.440 --> 21:50.067
Oh, look, a ugly water bug!

21:51.710 --> 21:52.768
Hey!

21:52.811 --> 21:53.835
Caught ya.

21:54.913 --> 21:56.175
Here she is.

22:00.619 --> 22:01.586
Night.

22:01.620 --> 22:02.587
Good night.

22:02.621 --> 22:04.612
Good night. You want
me to tuck you in?

22:04.656 --> 22:05.782
Golly can do it.

22:09.661 --> 22:11.595
"'The time has come,'
the Walrus said.

22:11.630 --> 22:13.120
"To talk of many things."

22:13.165 --> 22:14.655
"Of shoes and ships
and sealing wax."

22:14.700 --> 22:15.724
"Of cabbages and kings."

22:15.767 --> 22:17.098
"And why the sea
is boiling hot."

22:17.135 --> 22:18.432
"And whether
pigs have wings."'

22:18.470 --> 22:19.437
- Do you have any wings?
- Yeah.

22:19.471 --> 22:20.460
Let me see.

22:31.016 --> 22:32.244
Crap? No, no.

22:32.284 --> 22:33.808
This stuff is beyond crap.

22:33.852 --> 22:36.650
This is what crap wants
to be when it grows up.

22:36.688 --> 22:37.814
Listen to this.

22:37.856 --> 22:40.086
"A Question Corner
by Marion Hawthorne.

22:40.125 --> 22:42.525
"Horse riding,
for those who can afford it

22:42.561 --> 22:44.153
"is a very wonderful sport.

22:44.196 --> 22:46.994
"Every weekend,
my father takes me riding

22:47.065 --> 22:49.932
and we laugh together
as we ride."

22:51.470 --> 22:53.631
Does she mention
her mom pays for dork lessons?

22:53.672 --> 22:54.639
Man, once that

22:54.673 --> 22:57.608
disintegration ray
is complete... bzzt!

22:57.643 --> 22:59.338
She's molecular toast.

22:59.378 --> 23:00.606
- Oh, yeah.
- Oh, yeah.

23:00.646 --> 23:02.375
Mom and Dad's night out.

23:02.414 --> 23:05.281
Me and Golly's night in.

23:05.317 --> 23:06.511
Hello.

23:08.987 --> 23:10.147
What's that smell?

23:10.188 --> 23:11.951
Delicious
German bratwurst.

23:11.990 --> 23:13.958
We hate bratwurst.

23:13.992 --> 23:15.619
I love bratwurst.

23:15.661 --> 23:16.787
Since when?

23:17.996 --> 23:19.156
I'll get it!

23:19.197 --> 23:20.789
No. No, no. I will get it.

23:20.832 --> 23:22.356
I'll get it! I'll get it!
I'll get it!

23:22.401 --> 23:24.369
I'll get it!
I'll get it! I'll get it!

23:24.403 --> 23:25.597
I said I'll get it

23:25.637 --> 23:26.968
and I mean
I'll get it.

23:27.005 --> 23:28.529
- I got it!
- No.

23:28.574 --> 23:30.974
I'll get it!

23:31.009 --> 23:32.636
Good evening, Katherine.

23:32.678 --> 23:34.305
The veggie thief.

23:34.346 --> 23:35.643
Katherine?

23:35.681 --> 23:37.148
Harriet Ann Welsch,

23:37.182 --> 23:38.979
Mr. George Waldenstein.

23:39.017 --> 23:40.712
How do you do?

23:40.752 --> 23:43.312
Yeah.

23:43.355 --> 23:45.516
I've seen him around.

23:45.557 --> 23:47.354
Bet he stole that pineapple.

24:21.526 --> 24:22.493
Good soup.

24:22.527 --> 24:23.687
Harriet,

24:23.729 --> 24:25.060
where are your manners?

24:25.097 --> 24:26.064
I don't know.

24:26.098 --> 24:28.123
Maybe somebody stole them.

25:03.435 --> 25:05.096
Hey, you cheated.

25:06.304 --> 25:07.464
Oh, you win.

25:07.506 --> 25:08.700
My congratulations.

25:08.740 --> 25:10.674
Yeah, well, I know some stuff.

25:10.709 --> 25:12.108
So, you're

25:12.144 --> 25:13.111
a delivery boy?

25:13.145 --> 25:14.578
Mm-hmm.

25:14.613 --> 25:17.946
Well, no offense, but, uh,
you're like, what, 45?

25:17.983 --> 25:19.280
Ish.

25:19.317 --> 25:21.945
Shouldn't you be
a delivery man by now?

25:22.020 --> 25:23.510
Harriet!

25:23.555 --> 25:25.614
Well, Harriet, I'll tell you.

25:25.657 --> 25:27.955
Not long ago,
I had another life.

25:27.993 --> 25:30.086
I had a big business,
I had a lot of money,

25:30.128 --> 25:31.095
and you know what?

25:31.129 --> 25:34.496
I was the most
miserable man alive.

25:34.533 --> 25:36.467
So, one day,
I told my wife that...

25:36.501 --> 25:38.162
- Wife?
- I told my wife that I

25:38.203 --> 25:40.398
wanted to start all over
again and if she wanted to,

25:40.439 --> 25:41.838
she could start all over
with me.

25:41.873 --> 25:43.465
So what happened?

25:43.508 --> 25:46.306
Oh, she left me, but that's
all right, that was her choice.

25:46.344 --> 25:48.812
My choice was to become
a delivery boy... well, man.

25:48.847 --> 25:50.576
I don't have the
business, of course.

25:50.615 --> 25:51.741
I don't have the money.

25:51.783 --> 25:53.751
You know what?

25:53.785 --> 25:56.151
My life is sweet again.

25:58.790 --> 26:00.758
Hmm.

26:03.195 --> 26:04.423
The wurst!

26:04.463 --> 26:06.590
Oh, no! My wurst!

26:06.631 --> 26:07.757
No, no!

26:07.799 --> 26:10.063
Oh...

26:10.102 --> 26:12.070
Oh, Lord.

26:12.104 --> 26:13.366
Oh, no. No.

26:13.405 --> 26:14.497
Don't be sad, Katherine.

26:14.539 --> 26:15.938
This is a blessing
in disguise.

26:16.007 --> 26:17.770
That's a pretty
good disguise.

26:17.809 --> 26:18.833
Don't you see?

26:18.877 --> 26:20.469
The three of us
have to go out for dinner.

26:20.512 --> 26:21.479
- No.
- Yeah!

26:21.513 --> 26:23.947
Yes, dinner and a movie!

26:23.982 --> 26:25.882
Movie, movie, movie!
Come on, Golly!

26:25.917 --> 26:27.475
The idea seems
popular enough.

26:27.519 --> 26:28.713
Yes, but the Welschs...

26:28.754 --> 26:29.721
Will be out.

26:29.755 --> 26:31.950
Till million o'clock!

26:31.990 --> 26:34.652
- Oh, please, Golly.
- Please, oh, please?

26:34.693 --> 26:37.355
Oh, please, please,
please, oh, please.

26:37.395 --> 26:39.295
Oh, please, please, please.

26:39.331 --> 26:40.593
What the heck.

27:26.144 --> 27:27.168
This is absurd.

27:42.027 --> 27:42.823
Yes!

27:43.895 --> 27:45.726
Don't speak.

27:47.999 --> 27:51.662
Wait! Wait for me!
I'm not dead.

27:59.011 --> 28:00.638
Are you okay?

28:00.679 --> 28:02.909
Yeah.

28:02.948 --> 28:04.142
Hey.

28:04.182 --> 28:06.173
How come
all the lights are on?

28:06.218 --> 28:08.049
Where is my child?

28:08.086 --> 28:09.883
Uh-oh.

28:09.921 --> 28:11.445
Harriet? Harriet,
what are you doing

28:11.490 --> 28:12.457
in that contraption?

28:12.491 --> 28:13.924
Come in here at once.

28:13.992 --> 28:15.050
Miss Golly,
what are you doing

28:15.093 --> 28:16.890
with my child, at this hour,
without my consent?

28:16.928 --> 28:18.156
- Who is that?
- My name is...

28:18.196 --> 28:19.163
- Shut up!
- I'm sorry.

28:19.197 --> 28:20.664
We only went to dinner
and then a movie.

28:20.699 --> 28:22.633
Harriet is not
your daughter, Miss Golly.

28:22.667 --> 28:24.567
She is mine,
and you have no idea, none,

28:24.603 --> 28:26.127
what it is like
to come home and find

28:26.171 --> 28:27.934
- that your child is missing.
- We had no idea

28:28.006 --> 28:29.064
that you'd be home this soon.

28:29.107 --> 28:30.734
I don't care.
I don't care what you did

28:30.776 --> 28:31.834
or where you went or why.

28:31.877 --> 28:33.742
All I know is this
can never happen again.

28:33.779 --> 28:37.237
Miss Golly... you are fired.

28:37.282 --> 28:38.249
What?! No!

28:38.283 --> 28:39.580
Just a moment.

28:39.618 --> 28:41.677
This is my fault. Please.

28:41.720 --> 28:43.950
Well, it seems
awfully sudden.

28:43.989 --> 28:45.149
Actually...

28:45.190 --> 28:48.489
maybe it's not.

28:48.527 --> 28:50.961
I think you're right,
Mrs. Welsch.

28:50.996 --> 28:52.861
It is time for me to go.

28:53.865 --> 28:54.832
What?

28:54.866 --> 28:55.890
What?

28:55.934 --> 28:57.333
What?

29:00.205 --> 29:02.332
Now, look, I admit, I lost it...

29:02.374 --> 29:04.103
because, I just...
I was frightened.

29:04.142 --> 29:06.576
But the thing is, the fact is
we need you, Golly.

29:06.611 --> 29:08.579
We can't do it alone.

29:08.613 --> 29:11.514
We all spoke out of turn,
I think.

29:11.550 --> 29:13.245
None of this is causing...

29:13.285 --> 29:15.082
Absolutely not.

29:15.120 --> 29:16.087
Absolutely, no.

29:16.121 --> 29:18.715
I mean, I think we were
talking about...

29:18.757 --> 29:20.156
our feelings out there.

29:20.192 --> 29:22.057
You were afraid
and-and-and now

29:22.094 --> 29:24.358
what we should
be focusing on, right?

29:24.396 --> 29:25.556
Is-is Harriet.

29:25.597 --> 29:27.087
Look, I'm sorry.

29:27.132 --> 29:28.463
- I lost my head out there.
- Look. There.

29:28.500 --> 29:29.865
- No, no.
- I was just...

29:29.901 --> 29:31.926
but you can't go...
I mean, we need you.

29:32.037 --> 29:33.868
Harriet would never
stand for it.

29:33.905 --> 29:35.236
Please, won't
you reconsider?

29:35.273 --> 29:36.740
You know, it's not about

29:36.775 --> 29:38.208
what happened
outside tonight.

29:38.243 --> 29:39.232
It really isn't.

29:39.277 --> 29:40.437
But Golly...

29:40.479 --> 29:42.947
I just... no, I think it's time.
I really do.

29:43.014 --> 29:45.608
Harriet can take care of herself
now, so she should.

29:45.650 --> 29:46.742
But Harriet's just...

29:46.785 --> 29:47.911
She's just a little girl.

29:47.953 --> 29:49.443
You know, it's the right thing.

29:49.488 --> 29:51.251
It's the right thing
for all of us...

29:51.289 --> 29:56.283
for me, for you
and for Harriet.

29:56.328 --> 29:59.297
Are you sure?

29:59.331 --> 30:01.891
Yeah, I am.

30:11.710 --> 30:14.144
"'The time has come,"
the Walrus said,"

30:14.179 --> 30:15.669
"To talk of many things...

30:15.714 --> 30:18.774
"Of shoes and ships
and sealing wax..."

30:23.688 --> 30:26.156
"Of cabbages and kings...

30:26.191 --> 30:29.592
"And why the sea
is boiling hot...

30:29.628 --> 30:32.995
And whether pigs have wings."

30:56.821 --> 30:58.982
Where you going to go?

30:59.024 --> 31:01.015
Well, I don't really know.

31:01.092 --> 31:03.151
I'm thinking I may travel.

31:03.195 --> 31:06.722
Are you going to go be
some other kid's nanny now?

31:06.765 --> 31:09.962
And love them more than you?

31:10.068 --> 31:11.228
Never.

31:11.269 --> 31:14.705
Remember, in my life,
in this world

31:14.739 --> 31:17.708
there will always
only be one Harriet.

31:21.046 --> 31:22.638
So get back to work...
you've lost nearly

31:22.681 --> 31:23.909
an entire day
on your notebook.

31:23.949 --> 31:25.712
It doesn't matter.

31:25.750 --> 31:27.911
It doesn't matter?

31:27.953 --> 31:29.648
Did I hear you say
"It doesn't matter"?

31:29.688 --> 31:31.155
Because I thought
I heard you say

31:31.189 --> 31:32.156
"It doesn't matter,"

31:32.190 --> 31:33.680
but Harriet wouldn't say that,
would she?

31:33.725 --> 31:34.692
Now come on...

31:34.726 --> 31:36.421
just because
you're on your own,

31:36.461 --> 31:38.691
doesn't mean the world
stops turning,

31:38.730 --> 31:40.994
or that there are
no more fascinating people

31:41.066 --> 31:43.193
to observe and fill
your notebooks with.

31:43.235 --> 31:45.135
That's your job, Harriet.

31:45.170 --> 31:47.001
That's your job for life.

31:47.105 --> 31:49.266
And when you're all grown up

31:49.307 --> 31:51.571
and you sell
your first novel,

31:51.610 --> 31:53.976
I'll be first in line
at that bookstore,

31:54.012 --> 31:55.775
getting my autographed copy.

31:55.814 --> 31:58.544
I hope.

32:01.319 --> 32:03.344
I'm not going to cry.

32:04.623 --> 32:06.921
I'm not going to cry.

32:06.958 --> 32:08.425
I'm not going
to cry.

32:08.460 --> 32:10.052
Ah, it's okay to cry.

32:10.095 --> 32:11.960
But whatever you do,
don't laugh.

32:12.030 --> 32:13.429
No, Harriet,

32:13.465 --> 32:16.696
I will not tolerate laughter
as I leave, no.

32:17.769 --> 32:18.758
Hey...

32:18.803 --> 32:20.293
come here.

32:23.908 --> 32:25.773
You remember...

32:25.810 --> 32:28.278
a good spy can
get in there and fight.

32:52.237 --> 32:55.172
Good-bye, Harriet the Spy.

33:14.458 --> 33:15.823
I was kind of worried, you know?

33:15.860 --> 33:17.953
I kind of thought, "Well,
there's something wrong

33:17.995 --> 33:19.360
with me or something," and so...

33:21.799 --> 33:25.166
Growing up from girl to woman,

33:25.202 --> 33:27.796
there's so much to get used to.

33:27.838 --> 33:32.070
This is the time when a whole
new set of feelings unfold.

33:32.109 --> 33:36.637
Feelings about yourself
and your maturing body...

33:36.680 --> 33:40.980
Everything's the same
as when Golly was here.

33:41.085 --> 33:45.283
It looks the same...

33:45.322 --> 33:48.223
it smells the same...

33:48.259 --> 33:50.227
but there's this
tiny hole inside me

33:50.261 --> 33:51.819
that wasn't there before.

33:55.466 --> 33:58.458
It's like...

33:58.502 --> 34:00.697
like a splinter
in your finger...

34:04.008 --> 34:07.102
only this one's
right above my stomach.

34:19.456 --> 34:20.786
Harriet,

34:20.824 --> 34:22.416
are you okay?

34:22.458 --> 34:25.053
Uh-huh.

34:36.139 --> 34:39.438
Something's... different.

34:50.955 --> 34:52.752
No cats?

34:52.790 --> 34:56.521
How can Harrison Withers
not have a billion cats around?

35:14.812 --> 35:16.609
They finally nailed him.

35:27.625 --> 35:31.959
I will always remember
that face.

35:32.062 --> 35:38.092
That's the face you make
when you really lose something.

35:43.007 --> 35:47.239
Uh-oh, Frankie took the truck.

36:02.493 --> 36:04.051
Speak English!

36:04.094 --> 36:06.927
Oh, okay, you want us
to speak English, huh?!

36:06.997 --> 36:08.862
Well, you are a jerk, huh?

36:08.899 --> 36:11.561
I tell you, "Don't
take the truck.

36:11.602 --> 36:12.762
You smash the truck."

36:12.803 --> 36:14.100
Well, you tell me now,

36:14.138 --> 36:15.628
Mr. Wise Guy,
was one date worth it?

36:15.673 --> 36:16.935
...we have people
here shopping!

36:17.041 --> 36:18.508
Yeah.

36:23.347 --> 36:24.871
Hey, all right, Grandpa.

36:24.915 --> 36:26.075
It's cool, right?

36:26.116 --> 36:27.845
It wasn't a big deal, huh?

36:27.885 --> 36:29.182
I knew you'd
understand, right?

36:32.589 --> 36:36.252
Sometimes I think
families everywhere

36:36.293 --> 36:38.420
are exactly the same.

36:38.462 --> 36:40.123
Everybody get back to work.

36:40.164 --> 36:42.428
Mom, Dad, please?
Grandpa!

36:42.466 --> 36:44.661
Just calm down.

36:48.305 --> 36:49.294
Too exciting.

36:53.177 --> 36:55.702
$6.75.

37:11.195 --> 37:12.822
You got it or not?

37:27.377 --> 37:29.277
Hey, Sport.

37:29.313 --> 37:30.780
How you doing?

37:30.814 --> 37:33.339
Hi.

37:35.252 --> 37:38.744
Um, I saw you drop this outside.

37:38.789 --> 37:40.450
Oh...

37:41.859 --> 37:43.690
Thanks.

37:54.304 --> 37:56.329
I got to go.

38:08.486 --> 38:12.752
Now it's time for our annual
sixth grade holiday pageant.

38:12.790 --> 38:15.623
So... pageant ideas...

38:15.659 --> 38:18.150
who would like
to make a suggestion?

38:18.195 --> 38:20.060
Simon.

38:20.097 --> 38:21.325
Pirates.

38:21.365 --> 38:24.459
Okay.

38:26.137 --> 38:29.072
Good dramatic potential,
if not exactly seasonal.

38:29.106 --> 38:30.733
Anyone else?

38:32.576 --> 38:34.441
How 'bout the Manhattan Project?

38:34.478 --> 38:36.207
I can be J. Robert Oppenheimer

38:36.247 --> 38:37.942
and with the right chemicals,

38:38.048 --> 38:40.039
I know I can do
a mushroom cloud.

38:40.084 --> 38:42.075
That's impressive, Janie.

38:42.119 --> 38:46.055
But I believe there's
a taste issue involved.

38:46.090 --> 38:47.079
Ballet.

38:47.124 --> 38:48.284
Pilgrims.

38:48.325 --> 38:49.622
Musical.

38:49.660 --> 38:51.457
Swan Lake.

38:54.999 --> 38:56.364
Jazz.

38:56.400 --> 38:57.389
Vlad the lmpaler.

38:57.434 --> 38:59.527
Yeah, that's cool!

38:59.570 --> 39:03.097
I think the most excellent idea
for a pageant

39:03.140 --> 39:05.631
would be
a giant holiday feast.

39:05.676 --> 39:10.079
Something healthy, low in fat,
and very delicious, of course.

39:10.114 --> 39:12.548
There could be parts
for everybody.

39:12.583 --> 39:16.679
Uh, grains, vegetables

39:16.720 --> 39:20.451
and best of all,
a shiny, silver centerpiece.

39:20.491 --> 39:22.425
That's a very good idea, Marion.

39:22.459 --> 39:24.825
You could play the barf bag.

39:24.862 --> 39:27.729
She made me an onion.

39:27.765 --> 39:28.857
Tell me about it.

39:28.899 --> 39:32.300
"You, my dear,
are a great big squash."

39:32.336 --> 39:34.099
I'd like to squash her.

39:34.138 --> 39:36.402
I've got something better.
Come here.

39:42.880 --> 39:44.370
Smell this.

39:44.415 --> 39:45.609
Ugh!

39:45.649 --> 39:46.946
What is that?

39:47.017 --> 39:48.177
You like it?

39:48.219 --> 39:49.948
Wait, I mean you hate it.

39:50.020 --> 39:52.784
It's like something crawled
up my nose and then died.

39:52.823 --> 39:53.790
Excellent.

39:53.824 --> 39:55.621
It's a sulfur-based
alkaloid.

39:55.659 --> 39:57.718
I want it to chemically
fuse with combustibles.

39:57.761 --> 40:00.457
And, in English,
that would mean...

40:00.497 --> 40:01.623
Stink bomb.

40:01.665 --> 40:03.257
Stink bomb.

40:03.300 --> 40:04.961
We tape it to the
school air ducts,

40:05.002 --> 40:06.094
attach it to a timer,

40:06.136 --> 40:08.627
